The '''Healing Church in Rhode Island''' is a [[Rhode Island]]-based religious sect whose adherents believe that [[cannabis]] (or marijuana) is a "holy herb" and [[Entheogenic use of cannabis|use it in religious rituals]].<ref name="CannabisChurch">[http://turnto10.com/news/local/members-of-rhode-island-cannabis-church-arrested-on-marijuana-charges Members of Rhode Island cannabis church arrested on marijuana charges], [[WJAR]] ([[Sinclair Broadcast Group]]) (July 20, 2016).</ref> Leaders of the group attracted attention in 2015 for attempting to smoke marijuana in front of the [[Roger Williams National Memorial]] (a memorial to [[Roger Williams]], a pioneer of [[religious freedom]] and one of the smallest National Parks) as part of a religious service.<ref name="CannabisChurch"/><ref>Matt Reed, [http://turnto10.com/archive/healing-church-holds-cannabis-ceremony-in-providence "Healing Church" holds cannabis ceremony in Providence], [[WJAR]] ([[Sinclair Broadcast Group]]) (May 24, 2015).</ref> One of the church members said that [[bhang]] was consumed during the service on federal property, to avoid a no-smoking rule.<ref>{{cite journal|work=[[High Times]]|title=Religious cannabis already being put to the test in Rhode Island|first=Mike|last=Adams|date=June 2, 2015|url=http://hightimes.com/news/religious-cannabis-already-being-put-to-the-test-in-rhode-island/}}</ref> The following year, two leaders of the group were arrested and charged in connection with a marijuana grow operation.<ref name="CannabisChurch"/> Days before the arrest, the pair had filed a lawsuit in [[United States District Court for the District of Rhode Island|federal district court]], contending that enforcement of state anti-marijuana laws against those who use marijuana for religious purposes violates  the [[U.S. Constitution]].<ref>Paul Edward Parker, [http://www.providencejournal.com/news/20160720/leaders-of-healing-church-filed-federal-lawsuit-days-before-their-arrest-on-marijuana-charges Leaders of Healing Church filed federal lawsuit days before their arrest on marijuana charges], ''Providence Journal'' (July 20, 2016).</ref>

