{{Infobox museum | name = Museum of World Religions | native_name = 世界宗教博物館 | native_name_lang = zh | logo = | logo_upright = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = | image = 40024-Taipei-WRMuseum (7964474250).jpg | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | map_type = | map_relief = | map_size = | map_caption = | coordinates = <!-- {{Coord}} --> | former_name = | established = 2001 | dissolved = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | location = [[Yonghe District|Yonghe]], [[New Taipei]], [[Taiwan]] | type = [[Museum]] | accreditation = | key_holdings = | collections = | collection_size = | visitors = | founder = | executive_director = | leader_type = | leader = | director = | president = | ceo = | chairperson = | curator = | architect = | historian = | owner = | publictransit = [[Yongan Market Station]] | car_park = | parking = | network = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | embedded = }}
The '''Museum of World Religions''' ('''MWR'''; {{zh|c=世界宗教博物館|p=Shìjiè Zōngjiào Bówùguǎn}}) is a [[museum]] in [[Yonghe District]], [[New Taipei]], [[Taiwan]].<ref>Maria Reis Habito, [http://muse.jhu.edu/login?uri=/journals/buddhist-christian_studies/v022/22.1habito_m.html The Taipai, Taiwan, Museum of World Religions], ''[[Buddhist-Christian Studies]]'', [http://uhpjournals.wordpress.com/2002/11/30/buddhist-christian-studies-vol-22-2002/ Volume 22], 2002.</ref>
The museum was founded by Venerable [[Hsin Tao]] (心道), a Buddhist monk, and set up through the Ling Jiou Mountain Buddhist Foundation. The museum building was designed by [[Ralph Appelbaum Associates]],<ref>[http://www.raany.com/html/proj_03/portProj_WorldReligion.html Museum of World Religions: Project Description] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704082335/http://www.raany.com/html/proj_03/portProj_WorldReligion.html |date=2008-07-04 }}, [[Ralph Appelbaum Associates]] Incorporated.</ref> the designer of major American museums including the [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]] in [[Washington DC]] and the expansion of the [[Hayden Planetarium]] at the [[American Museum of Natural History]] in [[New York City]].<ref name="HDS">[http://www.hds.harvard.edu/news/article_archive/museum.html Two HDS Staff On Hand for Opening of Museum of World Religions in Taipei] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705091958/http://www.hds.harvard.edu/news/article_archive/museum.html |date=2008-07-05 }}, [[Harvard Divinity School]], [[Harvard University]], United States, 2002.</ref>
The Museum of World Religions was opened in 2001 by Hsin Tao. Further elaborate opening ceremonies were held on September 11 and in November 2002 with many religious leaders and others from around the world, including the President [[Chen Shui-bian]].<ref name="HDS" /> The Taiwanese architect and educator [[Han Pao-teh]] was the first curator.
The museum presents exhibits on ten different major [[Major religious groups|world religions]]. It also features a model called "Avatamsaka World" illustrating the [[Avatamsaka Sutra]].
==Transportation== The museum is accessible within walking distance North West from [[Yongan Market Station]] of the [[Taipei Metro]].
